subSubSection.paragraph:
Male description (
Figs. 1–7
). Body vestiture apparently uniform pale gray, the integument yellowish brown. Head (
Fig. 1–2
): Eyes separated by one or one and a half facet diameters; eye­bridge with four rows of facets; interocular suture somewhat arched and with a poorly visible dorsal middlemost spur; a row of five setae along the upper margin of each eye; the vertex rounded in outline, with a single median patch of scale alveoli leaving a small naked area in the upper central area which extends downward without reaching the level of the interocular suture; frontal patch of setae alveoli undivided, extending upward between the eyes to reach the level of the third facet (
Fig. 1
). Ascendant tentorial arms straight, narrow, as long as 8x its width; posterior tentorial arms composed of a pair of laterally sclerotized, nearly parallel, concave flanges in posterior view; maxillary apodeme nearly straight; posterior margin of the eyes sigmoidal in outline, and a postoccipital plate well separated by a suture (
Fig. 2
). Labellum bulbous with three or four long anteapical setae and two to four short spiniform setae in the internal margin near the apex, but without blunt teeth (as in 
Fig. 9
). Palpus as long as 0.36x antenna length, and about 1.1x as long as head height; proportion of palpomeres: 1.00: 1.42: 1.36: 1.46 (
Fig. 1
). Antennae as long as 0.5x wing length, with 14 flagellomeres; scape barrel­shaped, longer than the spherical pedicel; flagellomere 1 with node 2x as long as its own internode; subsequent flagellomeres similar to 1, but nodes progressively decreasing in size and internodes increasing in length to such an extent that flagellomere 10 has the node equal in length to the internode; each internode parallel sided, uniformly sclerotized but with a median transverse sulcus (
Fig. 3
); flagellomere 11 without internode; flagellomeres 12–14 small and globular, not fused, 12–13 nearly sessile but in a short broad pedunculus, 14 with a long pedunculus; a pair of “Y”­shaped ascoids present on flagellomeres 1–11, each with two large anterior branches and one shorter posterior branch; the last three flagellomeres only with the short spiniform sensilla (
Fig. 4
). Thorax: Wing length about 2.5x breadth; Sc ending at the level of the base of R 
1
; R 
5
ending at wing tip; base of M 
2
not connected; wing membrane without hairs; proportion of R 
2+3
:R 
3
= 2.9:2.8; M 
1+2
:M 
2
= 1.5:4.0. Genitalia with elaborate and symmetric aedeagus (
Figs. 5–7
). Cercopod with setae alveoli covering its surface, as long as 1.7x the lateral length of epandrium, bearing a clavate retinaculum which is as long as 0.3x the cercopod length; epandrium strongly bilobed apically, a little longer than wide, with two well separated lateral patches that do not reach the proximal portion and with a small pseudospiracular opening (
Fig. 6
). Gonocoxite subcylindrical, with an external lateral patch of setae alveoli, 0.64x as long as the gonostylus; gonocoxal apodemes broad and plate­like meeting beneath the aedeagal apodeme, only slightly expanded, with the internal margin nearly straight and convergent posteriorly. Gonostylus hirsute, straight, but ending in a sharp, entally curved apex, and with an external basal patch of setae alveoli and an irregular row of small setae in the internal apical margin (
Fig.
5). Aedeagus fusiform, with the apex acutely rounded in dorso­ventral view (
Fig. 5
), canoe­like in profile (
Fig. 7
), flanked by one pair of relatively long and nearly straight lateral shafts, except for a slightly ectally directed curvature of the apical portion; apex of lateral shafts reaching the apical fourth of aedeagus (
Fig. 5
); aedeagal apodeme broad and truncated; aedeagal sheath trapezoidal in dorso­ventral view. The hypandrium is slender and diadem­like (
Fig. 5
). Tergite 10 is globular with a long conical median fleshy projection (
Figs. 6–7
).

Female description (
Figs. 8–15
). Similar to the male except for the following features: palpus 0.36x as long as antenna; proportion of palpomeres: 1.0:1.2:1.2:1.3.

Antennae (
Figs. 11–12
) 0.46x as long as wing; flagellomeres 12–14 each with a longer petiole (
Fig. 12
). Wing 2.7x as long as width; proportion of R2+3:R3=1.0:1.0; M1+2:M2=1.0:2.2 (
Fig. 10
). Genitalia (
Figs. 13–15
): subgenital plate 0.67x as long as broad; distal lobes “X”­shaped, each with one sensory setae originating near the basal margin of the lobes at the level of the triangular genital sac (
Fig. 14
). Spermathecae complex as figured (
Fig. 13
); corpus spermathecae sculptured; median arms blade­like; posterior arms slightly divergent posteriorly; cercus long and gradually tapered (
Fig. 15
).
